r what it represents with a model kit and on paper and the nature of axial and equatorial substituents.";i:10;s:39:"Chair conformation axial vs equatorial.";i:11;s:101:"There are two general positions that a substituent can be in for a chair conformation of cyclohexane.";i:12;s:38:"That means notice this one right here.";i:13;s:113:"The other set consists of c h bonds that extend out to the periphery of the ring and are called equatorial bonds.";i:14;s:45:"Which chair conformation is lowest in energy.";i:15;s:100:"The lower energy chair conformation contains one axial methyl group and one equatorial methyl group.";i:16;s:70:"The higher energy chair conformation contains two axial methyl groups.";i:17;s:69:"The lower energy chair conformation contains two axial methyl groups.";i:18;s:50:"A The two chair conformations are equal in energy.";i:19;s:50:"The above chair flip in the video is slightly off.";i:20;s:48:"Remember that the direction of the groups up vs.";i:21;s:73:"Down should not change when going from axial to equatorial or vice versa.";i:22;s:109:"All the math is still correct here but I should have drawn the groups down instead of up on the second chair.";i:23;s:47:"Refer to the videos below for examples of this.";i:24;s:85:"In short A-value is the energy difference between axial and equatorial conformations.";i:25;s:150:"Lets say if A-value is 73 kJmol for the methyl group then the equatorial methylcyclohexane is more stable by 73kJmol than the axial methylcyclohexane.";i:26;s:35:"Below is the table of A values and.";i:27;s:349:"In the previous two posts we have talked about drawing the ring-flip of chair conformations and the A value 13-diaxial interactionsAnd we learned that for a given cyclohexane the axial conformer is less stable than the corresponding equatorial conformerFor example the energy difference of the axial and equatorial isopropyl cyclohexane is 92 kJmol.";i:28;s:28:"Each position has one axial.";i:29;s:26:"Each carbon has one axial.";i:30;s:36:"Each carbon also has one equatorial.";i:31;s:74:"The equatorial positions are going to face slightly opposite to the axial.";i:32;s:38:"That means notice this one right here.";i:33;s:33:"That one is facing up that axial.";i:34;s:65:"That means that my equatorial position should face slightly down.";i:35;s:88:"Every carbon on the chair conformation has 1 substituent axial and the other equatorial.";i:36;s:73:"If axial is up equatorial is down if equatorial is up then axial is down.";i:37;s:53:"Pick any ONE carbon and locate its axial substituent.";i:38;s:80:"Draw the equatorial substituent up or down the reverse of the axial substituent.";i:39;s:105:"But unlike the axial line this one will start on the carbon and form a slight angle outward of the chair.";i:40;s:111:"If the 3 peaks at 19 1715 all represent equatorial protons as they are shifted downfield compared to the axial.";i:41;s:50:"How does the peak at 13 represent 5 axial protons.";i:42;s:112:"Shouldnt they have split signals just like the equatorial protons due to the electronegativity of the oxygen an.";i:43;s:118:"Axial and Equatorial Hydrogens In the chair conformation of cyclohexane three hydrogens point up and three point down.";i:44;s:84:"These six hydrogens which point along an axis through the molecule are called axial.";i:45;s:262:"Chair conformation of cyclohexane is more stable than boat form because in chair conformaion the C-H bonds are equally axial and equatorial ie out of twelve C-H bonds six are axial and six are equatorial and each carbon has one axial and one equatorial C-H bond.";i:46;s:106:"In the chair conformation of cyclohexane bulky groups are usually placed in equatorial position NOT AXIAL.";i:47;s:170:"It prefers equatorial because axial position would experience steric hindrance from two axial hydrogens on the same side refered as 13-diaxial interactionThus equatorial.";i:48;s:30:"Axial vs equatorial positions.";i:49;s:158:"When converting projections of this D-Galactose I 